and a legatus to Q. Cicero in his government of Asia. Garatoni shows from Cieero‘s letters when Tubero came to him. Quintus after leaving his province (ante Kalendas Maias) reached Athens on the Ides of May (B.c. 58), and if Tubero left Asia at the same time as Quintus, he might easily have reached Thessalonica a little later (Ad Att. iii. 9). Cicero stayed with Plancius till the month of November, when Cicero returned to Dyrrachium, from which place he sent to his wife and to Atticus two letters which were written before he left Thessalonica (Ad Div. xiv. l 3 Ad Att. iii. 22).
